ty), Atman (the self), and Moksha (liberation).</p>\n<p>These philosophical texts have had a profound influence on Hindu spirituality and Indian philosophy at large. They form the basis for later schools such as Vedanta and have parallels with mystical traditions worldwide. The Upanishads’ introspective and speculative tone contrasts with the ritual-centric Samhitas and Brahmanas, highlighting the dynamic nature of the Vedas as sacred literature.</p>\n<h2>Comparative Perspectives: The Vedas and Other Religious Scriptures</h2>\n<p>When investigating what religion sacred text is the Vedas, it is helpful to compare them with other prominent religious scriptures. The Bible, Quran, Torah, and Buddhist Sutras each serve as foundational texts for their respective faiths, but the Vedas differ notably in composition, transmission, and authority.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Oral Tradition:</strong> The Vedas were preserved primarily through oral transmission for centuries before being written down, emphasizing memorization and chanting techniques to maintain textual integrity.</li>\n<li><strong>Structure:</strong> The Vedas are not a single cohesive narrative but a collection of texts serving ritual, liturgical, and philosophical purposes.</li>\n<li><strong>Divine Origin:</strong> The concept of Shruti underscores the belief in the Vedas’ eternal, uncreated status, unlike scriptures that are viewed as divinely inspired but authored by historical figures.</li>\n<li><strong>Multiplicity of Deities:</strong> The Vedas celebrate a pantheon of gods, contrasting with monotheistic traditions where scriptures center on a singular deity.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This comparative lens reveals how the Vedas function both as a religious text and as a cultural artifact reflecting the socio-religious milieu of ancient India.</p>\n<h3>The Role of the Vedas in Contemporary Hindu Practice</h3>\n<p>Despite their ancient origins, the Vedas continue to hold significant influence in modern Hinduism, albeit in 